<page_title>A Rhombohedral Structure of NaCl?</page_title>
<text>A Rhombohedral Structure of NaCl?

 
 
Instructions: Hold SHIFT and drag mouse to zoom in and out.

Under normal conditions, sodium chloride is composed of a face-centered cubic sublattice (FCC) of anions and another of cations, which interpenetrate each other. (Why does NaCl prefer this structure?)

The above model suggests a plausible structure for NaCl. This structure is also composed of two interwoven sublattices of  Na+ and Cl-. </text>
